Vermiculite attic insulation may contain asbestos and can present a contamination risk when disturbed during renovation, demolition, or maintenance activities.

## What is vermiculite insulation?

Vermiculite is a lightweight insulation material commonly found in older attic spaces. Some legacy vermiculite products, including materials historically sourced from Libby, Montana, may contain asbestos.

Not all vermiculite contains asbestos, so laboratory analysis is required to confirm whether asbestos is present.

## Why vermiculite can be a contamination risk

Vermiculite is not only a material identification issue. It can also become a contamination concern if fibres are released and spread beyond the original insulation.

Potential concerns include:

- Disturbance during attic access or renovation
- Migration of dust into adjacent spaces
- Contamination of surrounding materials and surfaces
- Exposure risk for workers or occupants

## When assessment is needed

Assessment is commonly required when:

- Renovation or demolition is planned
- Attic insulation is being accessed or disturbed
- A property transaction requires clarification of risk
- Building owners need defensible information for planning or disclosure

## How vermiculite is assessed

Western Health & Safety provides CIH-led assessment that may include:

- Review of building conditions and disturbance history
- Controlled sampling strategies
- Coordination of accredited asbestos laboratory analysis
- Risk-based interpretation and practical recommendations

Assessment focuses on whether vermiculite presents a meaningful exposure or contamination risk under real site conditions.

